  "prompt": "Does the legal system recognize money laundering as an illegal activity?",
  "response": "Yes, the legal system in most countries, including China, recognizes money laundering as an illegal activity. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds appear legal by concealing their true origin. This is typically done through a series of complex transactions designed to obscure the source of the funds.\n\nIn China, the legal framework against money laundering includes several key laws and regulations:\n\n1. **Criminal Law of the People's Republic of China**: Article 191 specifically criminalizes money laundering. Individuals or entities involved in money laundering can face severe penalties, including imprisonment and fines.\n\n2. **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**: Enacted in 2007 and amended in subsequent years, this law establishes a comprehensive legal framework to prevent and combat money laundering. It outlines the responsibilities of financial institutions, requires them to establish internal controls, and mandates reporting of suspicious transactions.\n\n3. **Regulations and Guidelines**: Various regulatory bodies in China, such as the People's Bank of China (PBOC) and the China Banking and Insurance Regulatory Commission (CBIRC), issue detailed regulations and guidelines to implement anti-money laundering measures. These include requirements for customer due diligence, record-keeping, and reporting of large and suspicious transactions.\n\n4. **International Cooperation**: China is also a member of international bodies such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. China collaborates with other countries to tackle cross-border money laundering activities.\n\nIn summary, the legal system in China, like in many other countries, recognizes money laundering as a serious criminal offense and has established robust laws and regulations to prevent and punish such activities.",
